Reasoning: This paper deals with computational methods for analyzing linguistic data, specifically the historical phonology of West Iranian languages. The paper employs a Bayesian approach to tease apart the different determinants of irregularity in patterns of West Iranian sound change. This methodology involves the use of hierarchical Dirichlet processes, which are commonly used in natural language processing and machine learning. Therefore, the most likely sub-category is cs.CL (Computation and Language). The paper also involves statistical modeling and probabilistic inferences, which are relevant to sub-categories such as cs.LG (Machine Learning) and cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence). The paper also deals with data analysis and modeling, which are relevant to sub-categories such as cs.SI (Social and Information Networks) and cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms).
